      "body" : "It is not useless: 1. It makes sure that multi-thread updating the vector is not going to mess up the internal of the list. 2. If you need to synchronize multiple operation you always need to explicit synchronize and do the operations.  In case of ArrayList, if you synchronize on &quot;multi operations&quot; but not single ones, the internal can be messed up.  CopyOnWriteArrayList is solving only specific problem which is not to replace every use of synchronized list.  (Anyway, I will recommend <code>Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList())</code> instead of Vector for synchronized list)"
